commentBody:
@John

I actually slapped in ENO reflexively, noticed the clue was [Rocker Brian], and changed it to MAY. 

Of course, that didn’t last.

@Paul

46A has appeared twice before, although both times clued as the name of a podcast.  (Amazing that calling a TV show "Schitt's Creek" made it OK for announcers to say another "dirty word" aloud on promos!)

SNAFU has appeared 100 times.  If SNAFU is ok, why not today's word?

@Gary
elsewhere I posted a link to "Backwater"!!

But @ALH et al., I feel your pain. I too entered Dr. May's name first. [In addition to creating new sounds with an electric guitar, Sir Brian Harold May is a PhD astrophysicist.]

@Francis

Well it's British and a put-down of a French product, but I suspect that the letters were a good fit for the crosses and the quote was found to clue it.

Much better than the simple "English blue-veined cheese" don't you think?

@Francis
Definitely a clue was found to fit the entry. 
I know I could look this up somewhere, but I’m guessing ROQUEFORT hasn’t made its way an NYT grid.

@Andrzej
@Al In Pittsburg

No, I was not waxing philosophical. 😀

It just seems strange to me to dredge up a completely boring sentence from a man who was anything but boring.  

It would be like quoting Einstein as saying "I prefer boxers to briefs" while he was working on his field equations.

@Francis

But that's human interest!

I mean, wouldn't you like to know Cleopatras favorite dish? Enheduannas favorite dog? Whether I sleep nude or in PJs?

@Andrzej

😂

"Alex, the question is 'What are three things that would never occur to me to wonder about in a tera-year.'"

@Francis

Oh don't be coy.

It's PJs.

@Matt

It also says my dead is my wife, and when I tell it it's not, it proceeds to tell me a Polish government minister is my wife, even though info on who her husband is - it's not me - is available online.

So... neener neener!

@Petrol
I was concerned with your #2, but relaxed about that with #5. The cheese here is incredible. BIG selling point for me, and I’m lactose intolerant. I don’t let that pesky fact get in the way of enjoying French cheese. 

The Brits, however, rule with beer, at least over the French. And by that I mean ale, etc. I was in Scotland a couple of weeks ago and partook in some fine beverages. Oh yeah, whisky too.

@Mike
There you go again....grasping at straws.
Or is that gasping?

@Petrol

It's also where we get agglutinative, as in languages in which suffixes are stuck onto the end.

It's often amazing how words are related to other words!

@Steve L

Thanks for your reply. "Ka" is just one particle I can remember. There are many. Some show a word is the subject of a sentence. Some make a word into a verb or action word. I believe you change "England" into "English language" by adding a particle, etc., etc., etc. The particles delineate the grammatical structure of the sentence. What is subject, what is verb, what is object, etc.

One thing I remember is this. If you want to say "The people are riding on the bus," you're basically saying "The riding-on-bus-people exist." The particles let you change "people" into "riding-on-bus-people"! It was a long time ago.

@Gareth et al.
respectfully disagree. I'm a Brian May fan and I entered him first, but ENO has enough rock credentials [Hall of Fame 2019, Roxy Music, Bowie, Talking Heads, Devo, U2, Here Come The Warm Jets, Taking Tiger Mountain (By Strategy), Another Green World, Before and After Science] to qualify as a Friday-worthy misdirect.

@RobJ 
I too had ivAnS which screwed me up for quite a while. And as I said elsewhere, I was even wrong about it--he was Ivan IV.

@Steve L

Is there a category beyond "Very Hard"?
(Asking for a friend.)

@Spenser
Please, skew them!
I signed up for the (free) xwstats to do my bit in skewing them back toward reality.

@D Ah, there we go! 

This puzzle was pretty miserable ngl.

No place to get a foothold. A lot of esoteric answers and hyper-specific trivia. If you liked it, cool. I didn’t enjoy it in the slightest. Should have ran on a Saturday imo.

@D
TIL ngl.
I loved it, but if this was this week's Friday I tremble at what tomorrow (or 10pm tonight) holds. But I tremble in a good way.

@The X-Phile
For CHEDDAR to be noteworthy (or worth a hunt) you would need more (like *Tillamook* cheddar or some such) because there is a lot of pedestrian cheese lurking out there...
Now Orwell's search...that narrows things down from "bleu cheese" to "Roquefort" to... [other iterations]..to the peak.

@Rich in Atlanta

Oh, wow!  That's quite a story.

My father was in WWII as well.  He didn't talk about it much.  Did yours talk about his experiences as a POW?

@ad absurdum
"I'm still, I'm still"

(Southside Bronx)

@Ace

I wondered if the clue/answer pairs are chosen to have possible wrong answers.

I used to write a lot of multiple choice tests.  I could make them much harder to giving wrong answers that would result from how I knew they would do it incorrectly.  We called them "distractors", and it was an art form.

@Niall
They are not particularly light in color--there is usually a brownish  outside "skin" (as with an onion, which is also a bulb)-- but they are smaller than many bulbs, though not the smallest.  My rain lilies and the blue-bells I once planted are very small.  
The clue might be a bit of a stretch, but all's fair in love and puzzles.

@RayinVa
Now, see?  This is how different we can be.
I got my toehold and strong start down there with the DRYADS and HENRI, plus I knew JENNY thanks to Marguerite Henry and _Brighty of the Grand Canyon_....  (she also wrote _Misty of Chincoteague_ and more.)  For a good while, that corner was all I had as I scratched and scrambled for another clue I could be sure of.  (Plenty of "Oh, Duh" moments.)

@MFSTEVE
I’ve got youngsters who call me Bobo (as in Bob-oh). Pretty sure they don’t think I’m groovy, but I hope your kids do (think you’re groovy)

Agree, enjoyable puzzle experience!

@Francis, I find them mealy and flavorless! I'm on your wife's side on this one!

My husband and I attend an apple and cider festival in western Massachusetts every November. Heirloom apples are a big focus. Spitzenberger, Roxbury Russet, and many more. Our favorite orchard is Clarkdale Fruit Farms in Deerfield, MA. 

<a href="https://clarkdalefruitfarms.com" target="_blank">https://clarkdalefruitfarms.com</a>/

@Francis

They were the dominant apple in my family, as well. When I was head chef at a summer camp, even served them to children. I deeply regret the emotional trauma they're probably experiencing till this day. But, as they say, hurt people hurt people.

I don't know, it seems like there were fewer options and they were just so ubiquitous.

@Roberto

For 1D, let me suggest you see "Cool Runnings" about the Old Limpic Jamaican BOBSLED team, to help you forever love all things BOBSLED.

Agreeing that the DAFFODIL clue probably turned one corner too many, but then there's all that lonely cloud-wandering most of us did in high school with that old Wordsmith William, so that word's worth Something. Right?

@Hugh

Wow. I'm impressed.  I was pushing the 1-hour mark.

But I had two young cats who were ignoring my DO NOT DISTURB sign.

@Sean
Well I'm not Barry, but I can tell you that there are a lot of words allowed in the grids that will cause a comment to get snagged by the EMU. Most of those messages eventually get released once they've been reviewed by a human, but that can take hours. Like, 8 hours. 

Come back here tomorrow and your snagged comment may be here.

@Lynn
One of the comments was in Wednesday. I understand that a bot is reviewing them and approving or denying them.  If a comment from Wednesday hasn't been approved by now, it's not likely to ever get approved.  At this point, it's no longer timely.  

I've avoided using that "phrase" just for this reason, and usually substitute something with heck.  It's still overkill.

@Joe
Not elite....just experienced.
Don't let yourself off the hook so readily.  Put in thetime, solve more puzzles, read columns and comments andpickup solving strategy.
